problem statment

xyz co's 2014-2018 sales data to identify key revenue and profit drivers across products, channels and regions, uncover sessional trends and outliers, and aligns perforamnce against budgets. use these insights to optimize pricing, promotions and market expansion for sustainable growth and reduced concentration risk

In[48]:
# Convert 'order_date' to datetime format (safe even if it's already in correct format)
df['order_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['order_date'], format='%Y-%m-%d')

# Create a new column for year-month to group by
df['year_month'] = df['order_date'].dt.to_period('M')

# Group by year-month and sum the revenue
monthly_sales = df.groupby('year_month')['revenue'].sum().reset_index()

# Convert back to timestamp for plotting
monthly_sales['year_month'] = monthly_sales['year_month'].dt.to_timestamp()

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.lineplot(data=monthly_sales, x='year_month', y='revenue', marker='o', linewidth=2.5)
plt.title('Monthly Sales Revenue', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Month', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Revenue', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

In[52]:
# Ensure order_date is in datetime format
df_new['order_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['order_date'], format='%Y-%m-%d')

# Extract calendar month name and number
df_new['month'] = df_new['order_date'].dt.month
df_new['month_name'] = df_new['order_date'].dt.strftime('%b')  # 'Jan', 'Feb', etc.

# Group by calendar month and sum revenue across all years
monthly_seasonality = df_new.groupby(['month', 'month_name'])['revenue'].sum().reset_index()

# Sort by month number to keep calendar order
monthly_seasonality = monthly_seasonality.sort_values('month')

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.lineplot(data=monthly_seasonality, x='month_name', y='revenue', marker='o', linewidth=2.5)
plt.title('Overall Monthly Sales Trend (Seasonality Across Years)', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Month', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Total Revenue (All Years)', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Step 1: Group by product_name and sum the revenue
top_products = df_new.groupby('product_name')['revenue'].sum().reset_index()

# Step 2: Sort and select top 10

sns.set(style="whitegrid")

plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.barplot(data=top_products, x='product_name', y='revenue',
            hue='product_name', palette='Blues_d', legend=False)

plt.title('Top 10 Products by Revenue', fontsize=16)

plt.ylabel('Total Revenue', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')  # Rotate x labels for readability

plt.show()

In[72]:
# 2. Calculate the profit and profit margin for each transaction.
# Profit is Revenue - Cost.
df_new['profit'] = df_new['revenue'] - df_new['total unit cost']

# Profit Margin is (Profit / Revenue) * 100 to get a percentage.
df_new['profit_margin_pct'] = (df_new['profit'] / df_new['revenue']) * 100

# 3. Group the data by 'channel' and calculate the mean profit margin.
# We then sort the values in descending order to easily see the highest margin channels.
average_profit_margin = df_new.groupby('channel')['profit_margin_pct'].mean().reset_index()
average_profit_margin = average_profit_margin.sort_values(by='profit_margin_pct', ascending=False)

# 4. Set the aesthetic style for the plot.
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")

# 5. Create the bar plot to visualize the average profit margin.
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.barplot(
    x='channel',
    y='profit_margin_pct',
    data=average_profit_margin,
    palette='viridis',
      hue='channel',
    legend=False
)

# 6. Add a title and labels for clarity.
plt.title('Average Profit Margin by Channel', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Sales Channel', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Average Profit Margin (%)', fontsize=12)

# 7. Add text annotations to each bar to display the exact value.
# The 'ha' and 'va' parameters are for horizontal and vertical alignment.
for index, row in average_profit_margin.iterrows():
    plt.text(
        index,
        row['profit_margin_pct'] + 1,
        f"{row['profit_margin_pct']:.2f}%",
        ha='center',
        va='bottom'
    )

# 8. Adjust the plot layout and display the final result.
plt.ylim(0, average_profit_margin['profit_margin_pct'].max() * 1.2) # Adjust y-axis to make room for annotations
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 2. Calculate the profit and profit margin for each transaction.
# Profit is Revenue - Cost.
df_new['profit'] = df_new['revenue'] - df_new['total unit cost']

# Profit Margin is (Profit / Revenue) * 100 to get a percentage.
df_new['profit_margin_pct'] = (df_new['profit'] / df_new['revenue']) * 100

# 3. Group the data by 'channel' and calculate the mean profit margin
average_profit_margin = df_new.groupby('channel')['profit_margin_pct'].mean().reset_index()
average_profit_margin = average_profit_margin.sort_values(by='profit_margin_pct', ascending=False)

# --- New Code for Customer Segmentation: Revenue vs. Profit Margin ---

# 14. Group the data by 'customer_name' to get total revenue and average profit margin.
customer_segmentation = df_new.groupby('customer_name').agg(
    total_revenue=('revenue', 'sum'),
    average_profit_margin=('profit_margin_pct', 'mean')
).reset_index()

# 15. Create a scatter plot for customer segmentation.
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.scatterplot(
    x='total_revenue',
    y='average_profit_margin',
    data=customer_segmentation,
    palette='plasma',
    hue='customer_name', # Note: Using 'customer_name' for hue will create many colors if you have many customers.
    legend=False
)
plt.title('Customer Segmentation: Revenue vs. Profit Margin', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Total Revenue ($)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Average Profit Margin (%)', fontsize=12)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

#Code for Correlation Heatmap ---

# 16. Select the numerical columns for the correlation matrix.
numerical_df = df_new[['revenue', 'total unit cost', 'order_quantity', 'unit_price', 'profit', 'profit_margin_pct', 'lat', 'lon']]

# 17. Calculate the correlation matrix.
correlation_matrix = numerical_df.corr()

# 18. Create the heatmap.
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.heatmap(
    correlation_matrix,
    annot=True,
    cmap='coolwarm',
    fmt=".2f",
    linewidths=.5,
    linecolor='black'
)
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap of Numerical Variables', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
